                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12860842" author="tsuna" created="Mon, 26 Apr 2010 07:45:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Patch that fixes the issue.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12861029" author="tlipcon" created="Mon, 26 Apr 2010 18:26:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;What does version null mean?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12861167" author="tsuna" created="Mon, 26 Apr 2010 23:30:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;In that case, as I wrote above, I didn&apos;t change &lt;tt&gt;hbase.rootdir&lt;/tt&gt; so it was pointing to the default, which I believe is &lt;tt&gt;/tmp/hbase-$USER&lt;/tt&gt;, and this directory didn&apos;t exist.  Normally the code is supposed to automatically create the directory if it doesn&apos;t exist, but for some reason it didn&apos;t.  This is another story though.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12861168" author="tsuna" created="Mon, 26 Apr 2010 23:32:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Oh and by the way, it seems that {{$&lt;/p&gt;
{HBASE_HOME}
&lt;p&gt;/bin/hbase migrate}} doesn&apos;t exist anymore, since when I ran it I got a nice &lt;tt&gt;Exception in thread &quot;main&quot; java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: org/apache/hadoop/hbase/util/Migrate&lt;/tt&gt;...&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12861185" author="stack" created="Tue, 27 Apr 2010 00:27:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The Migrate.java got removed as part of the cleanup of TRUNK removing deprecated stuff:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;
------------------------------------------------------------------------
r816014 | jgray | 2009-09-16 16:59:51 -0700 (Wed, 16 Sep 2009) | 1 line

HBASE-1822  Remove the deprecated APIs (incompatible change)
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My guess is that the thought was that a new Migrate would be made when we had something to actually Migrate.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The removal of the Migrate class may have been a bit of over-enthusiastic pruning but we can probably live with things as they currently are until a 0.21 version of hbase.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;@Benoit: I could commit this patch as is and we address improving the &apos;null&apos; message in another issue?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12861233" author="tsuna" created="Tue, 27 Apr 2010 04:22:55 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yeah, I think it makes sense to commit this tiny trivial lil patch, it can only help IMO.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12863048" author="stack" created="Sat, 1 May 2010 20:14:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Applied branch and trunk.  Resolving.  This issue makes the message more &apos;useful&apos;.  Could be better and not output &apos;null&apos; but its better than what was there before.  Thanks for the patch Benoit.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12866847" author="stack" created="Wed, 12 May 2010 23:52:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Marking these as fixed against 0.21.0 rather than against 0.20.5.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13258188" author="chen.ning" created="Fri, 20 Apr 2012 12:40:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi All, I met this problem in my environment. Fortunately, I found this has been fixed here, as a freshman, I don&apos;t know how to apply this fix into my environment since I only see a patch file which can&apos;t be applied to my environment, any suggestion?  Thank you.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13258199" author="chen.ning" created="Fri, 20 Apr 2012 12:47:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Forget to ask, is there any way to work this problem around? Thank you.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13259035" author="tsuna" created="Sun, 22 Apr 2012 07:27:39 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;@chenning, this isn&apos;t a good place to ask for support, send an email to the user mailing list.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;At this point you should be using a version of HBase that&apos;s much newer than the one in which this fix was made, so you shouldn&apos;t need to apply this fix.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15016966" author="lars_francke" created="Fri, 20 Nov 2015 12:41:24 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This issue was closed as part of a bulk closing operation on 2015-11-20. All issues that have been resolved and where all fixVersions have been released have been closed (following discussions on the mailing list).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
